'''Yamada-Hōma Kofun Group''' (山田・宝馬古墳群) refers to an assemblage of kofun (ancient Kofuns) located in [[:en:Shibayama, Chiba|Shibayama]], Sanbu District, [[:en:Chiba Prefecture|Chiba Prefecture]], Japan.  

== Overview ==  
The Yamada-Hōma Kofun Group spans the Yamada and Hōma areas of Shibayama Town. It is distributed across a plateau rising 40–45 meters above sea level, situated between the tributaries of the [[:en:Kuriyama River|Kuriyama River]], namely the {{ill|Takaya River (Kuriyama River Basin)|ja|高谷川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takaya River (Kuriyama River Basin)|qq=|1=Takaya River (Kuriyama River Basin)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11672847}} and the {{ill|Kido River (Chiba Prefecture)|ja|木戸川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kido River (Chiba Prefecture)|qq=|1=Kido River (Chiba Prefecture)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11518414}}.  

Historically, the Hōma Kofun Group comprised 4 keyhole-shaped tumuli and 66 round mounds, while the Yamada-Asakura Kofun Group included 7 keyhole-shaped tumuli and 157 round mounds. However, many have since been lost. A survey conducted in 1981 during construction associated with [[:en:Narita International Airport|Narita International Airport]] identified 6 remaining keyhole-shaped tumuli and 20 round mounds across the entire Yamada-Hōma area. The keyhole-shaped tumuli are relatively small, with mound lengths of 30–40 meters.  

Several of the keyhole-shaped tumuli excavated include:  

- '''Mound 35 (Hōma Kofun):''' This tumulus, 30 meters in length, features a box-type Sarcophagus. Excavations yielded iron arrowheads, and cylindrical, human-shaped, and artifact-shaped haniwa were discovered arranged around the mound.  

- '''Mound 65 (Hyōzuka Kofun):''' Measuring 35 meters in length, it contains a horizontal stone chamber. burial goods discovered include a bronze bowl, straight swords, gilded earrings, beads of natsume and glass, and other items.  

- '''Mound 127:''' With a mound length of 34 meters, a rear-circle diameter of 21.6 meters, and a front-section width of 21 meters, this tumulus revealed a surviving moat measuring 5–6.5 meters wide. Numerous human, animal, and cylindrical haniwa were recovered from the moat. Particularly, the constriction area on the mound’s eastern side displayed a dense arrangement of haniwa.  

- '''Mound 164 (Niwa-tori-zuka Kofun):''' At 40 meters in length, this tumulus features a box-type Sarcophagus in its constriction area. Excavations revealed straight swords, silver knives, iron arrowheads, earrings, horse fittings, and other burial goods. Cylindrical and various shaped haniwa, such as human, house, and animal figurines, were found encircling the mound. These haniwa provide critical examples of how such burial goods were arranged on Bōsō Peninsula kofun.  

Many round tumuli also contain box-type Sarcophaguss. The majority of excavated tumuli date to the latter half of the 6th century and exhibit characteristics of a cluster-type kofun group.  

